{{>header}}

  <div id="content">
    
    <div class="intro">Keep sensitive info out of your chat logs &amp; email.</div>
    {{#err}}<p class="err">{{err}}</p>{{/err}}
    <form id="" method="post" action="/create">
      <ul class="nav">
        <li class="primary">
          <input type="radio" id="shareRadio" name="kind" value="share" checked="checked" /> <label for="shareRadio">Paste it here!</label> 
          <span class="context">(e.g. a secret phrase, a special link, a bad joke etc)</span>
          <textarea name="secret" class="secretValue" rows="3" cols="80"></textarea>
        </li>
        <li class="secondary">
          <input type="radio" id="generateRadio" name="kind" value="generate" /> <label for="generateRadio">Or generate a short, unique secret</label> <span class="context">(e.g. for a temporary password)</span>
        </li>
        <div class"optionToggle"><a href="javascript:OptionsToggle();">More options</a></div>
        <div id="options">
          <input type="text" name="passphrase" value="" /> Enter a passphrase that only your recipient will know
        </div>
        <span id="fire" class="button"><button type="submit">Create a secret link*</button></span>
      </ul>
    </form>
    <div class="intro2"><em>* A secret link is available only one time and then it disappears forever.</em></div>
    <div id="faq">
      <h3>F.A.Q.</h3>
      <h4>Why would I use this?</h4>
      <p>When you send people passwords and private links via email or chat, there are copies of that information stored in many places. If you use a one-time link instead, the information persists for a single viewing which means it can't be read by someone else later. This allows you to send sensitive information in a safe way knowing it's seen by one person only. Imagine hearing 'This message will self destruct!' right after the recipient has loaded it.</p>
      
      <h4>Can I retrieve a secret that has already been shared?</h4>
      <p>Nope. We literally can only show it once. After that it's gone.</p>
      
      <h4>Why should I trust you?</h4>
      <p>In addition to being really cool guys, we can't really do anything with your information. If it's just a password for example, we don't know the username or even the application that the credentials are for.</p>
      
      <h4>Who are you guys?</h4>
      <p>We're <a href="http://delanotes.com/">Delano</a> and <a href="http://identi.ca/xopher">Chris</a>, the guys behind the <a href="https://www.blamestella.com/" title="Stella: The future of Web Monitoring">Blamey &amp; Stella Information Co</a>. It's the web monitoring service of the future. One-time Secret is one of our side-projects.</p>
      
    </div>
  </div>
  
